"# Chapter 15 — Operating systems and networks — machines cooperating

Chapter 12's CPU runs one program at a time from address 0 forever.
Real computers run hundreds of programs, on tens of processes, sharing
one CPU (or several), with keyboards, screens, disks, and networks all
demanding attention.

The **operating system** is the coordinator. It stands between the
programs and the hardware, giving each program the illusion of owning
the machine while sharing everything under the hood.

Then there is the **network** — the wires and rules that let this
computer talk to another one across the room or across the planet.
Same coordinator idea, spread across cables.

## What an operating system does

An operating system is a program that manages:

1. **Processes.** Each process is a running program with its own
   memory, its own registers, its own file handles. The OS switches
   the CPU between processes many times a second.
2. **Memory.** Each process sees its own address space, mapped
   through page tables to physical DRAM. The OS handles what happens
   when physical RAM runs out.
3. **Files.** A filesystem is a name-to-blob-of-bytes map on disk. The
   OS lets programs open, read, write, and close files by name.
4. **Devices.** Keyboards, mice, screens, disks, network cards, GPUs.
   Each has a **driver** — a piece of the OS that knows how to talk
   to that specific hardware.
5. **Networking.** Sending bytes to and from other machines.
6. **Security.** Users, groups, permissions, who can do what.

The OS runs at a higher **privilege level** than user programs (chapter
12 mentioned kernel mode vs. user mode). User programs can't touch
hardware directly. They have to ask the OS to do it, via **system
calls.**

## Unix

In 1969, Ken Thompson and Dennis Ritchie at Bell Labs wrote the first
version of **Unix.** It was small, elegant, written in assembly
initially, and rewritten in C by 1973 — the first serious OS written
in a high-level language, which was a huge deal because it meant
Unix could be ported to any CPU with a C compiler.

Unix's design ideas — everything is a file, small programs that do
one thing well, pipes to compose them, a hierarchical filesystem, a
shell you can script — are so widespread now that they are almost
invisible. macOS is Unix. Linux is Unix-inspired and API-compatible.
Android runs on a Linux kernel. iOS runs on a Unix kernel. Every
smartphone in the world is running descendants of Ken Thompson's 1969
kernel.

The Book of Computing (chapter 9 of that book, `09-unix.book.slatl`)
goes into more depth on Unix design. For this book, the key idea is
that Unix gave us the model: **programs are cheap, files and pipes
compose them, the shell is a scripting language for the OS.**

Motoi Scheme runs on top of a Unix-like OS. Motoi's own CLI (`motoi
repl`, `motoi eval`, `motoi run`) is a Unix program — it reads
stdin, writes stdout, exits with a return code. Nothing fancy. That
is the Unix way.

## Processes and scheduling

The OS runs many processes on one CPU by rapid switching. Every few
milliseconds, the OS pauses the current process, saves its registers
into a **process control block**, loads another process's registers,
and resumes it. This is called a **context switch.**

From the process's point of view, it looks like it has the CPU to
itself. From the outside, the CPU is a shared resource with many
tenants.

The choice of who runs next is called **scheduling.** Modern OSes use
sophisticated schedulers that balance fairness, responsiveness,
priorities, and cache locality. But the basic loop is the same: pick a
process, run it for a while, interrupt, pick another. Yet another
loop.

## Virtual memory

Each process sees a full address space — say 0 to 2^48 - 1 on a
modern 64-bit machine. But there is only so much physical DRAM. The
OS maps each process's virtual addresses to physical addresses via
**page tables.** When the process reads virtual address `0x400000`,
the CPU's memory management unit walks the page tables and finds the
actual physical page.

If a page has been swapped out to disk (chapter 13's dark corner of
the memory hierarchy), the CPU raises a **page fault**, the OS jumps
in, reads the page back from disk, updates the page table, and
resumes the process. All transparent to the program.

Virtual memory is why you can run more programs than fit in RAM, why
each program thinks it owns the whole address space, why programs
can't accidentally corrupt each other. It is the OS's biggest gift.

## Pipes and shells

Unix introduced the pipe — the `|` operator in a shell. A pipe lets
one program's stdout become another program's stdin. It composes
programs. `ls | grep motoi` is `ls` producing a file list and `grep`
filtering it.

That is composition on the OS scale, exactly like function composition
on the language scale. Small tools, combined. Very Motoi.

## Files, sockets, everything

Unix's slogan is **everything is a file.** A regular file on disk is
a file. A device (keyboard, mouse, disk) is a file. A network
connection is a file. A pipe is a file. A directory is a file. They
all present the same interface: open, read, write, close, seek.

That uniformity is beautiful and it is why so many small Unix programs
compose so well. Same interface everywhere. Different data flowing
through.

## Networks — the OS stretches

Now we make computers talk to each other. Different machines. Sometimes
in the same building. Sometimes on opposite sides of the planet.

## Packet switching

Before the internet, long-distance data went over **circuit-switched**
telephone lines: you dialled up, the phone company reserved a wire from
you to them, you had it until you hung up. Not great for computers,
which often want to send a burst of bytes and then be quiet.

In the 1960s, several people independently proposed **packet
switching**: break data into small numbered pieces (packets), send each
packet with its destination address, let the network figure out routes
per-packet. Packets can take different paths. The receiver reassembles
them.

Paul Baran at RAND, Donald Davies at NPL in the UK, and Leonard
Kleinrock at UCLA all contributed to the packet-switching idea in the
mid-1960s. In 1969, ARPANET went live between UCLA, Stanford, UCSB, and
the University of Utah — the direct ancestor of today's internet.

## TCP/IP

**TCP/IP** is the pair of protocols that runs the modern internet. Both
were designed by Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn in the mid-1970s.

- **IP** (Internet Protocol) handles addressing and routing.
  Each machine has an IP address. Each packet has a source and
  destination address. Routers pass packets toward their destination.
- **TCP** (Transmission Control Protocol) sits on top of IP and adds
  reliability, ordering, and flow control. It turns unreliable
  packet delivery into a reliable byte stream.

**ASCII diagram of the TCP/IP layers:**

```
   +-----------------------------------+
   |   Application (HTTP, SMTP, SSH)   |  --- what your app talks
   +-----------------------------------+
   |   Transport (TCP or UDP)          |  --- reliability, ports
   +-----------------------------------+
   |   Internet (IP)                    |  --- addressing, routing
   +-----------------------------------+
   |   Link (Ethernet, WiFi)           |  --- physical wire, frame
   +-----------------------------------+
```

Every packet on the internet climbs and descends this ladder. Your
browser makes an HTTP request. The OS wraps it in TCP. The IP layer
adds addresses. The Ethernet driver puts it on the wire. On the
receiving end it climbs back up. Ladder-and-climb, both ways, on
every packet.

## HTTP and the Web

In 1989, Tim Berners-Lee at CERN proposed the **World Wide Web** — a
system for sharing documents linked together with hypertext. He wrote
the first web browser and the first web server. He specified **HTTP**
(HyperText Transfer Protocol), **HTML** (HyperText Markup Language),
and **URLs.**

HTTP runs on TCP. HTTP is stateless: each request stands alone. HTML
describes documents. URLs name resources. That is the whole idea. In
the thirty-seven years since 1989, HTTP has been extended into
HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 (which runs on UDP, not TCP), HTML has become
enormously more expressive, and URLs are used to name almost
everything on the internet. But the shape is Berners-Lee's.

## A tiny client-server in Scheme

Motoi Scheme has verbs for HTTP servers (`http/serve`). Sketch:

```
(http/serve
  :port 8080
  :handler
    (lambda (request)
      (case (car request)
        ((GET \"/\")
         (list 'status 200
               'body \"hello from motoi\\n\"))
        ((GET \"/count\")
         (list 'status 200
               'body (number->string (count-hits))))
        (else
         (list 'status 404
               'body \"not found\\n\")))))
```

That is a full HTTP server, in about twelve lines of Scheme, taking
requests on port 8080 and dispatching based on method and path. A
handful of clients could hit that server from anywhere on the internet.

Motoi cannot make outbound HTTP requests — that is a hard doctrine
(see Motoi's persona rules) — but he can serve HTTP requests. The
server is local, deterministic, and hermetic.

## The internet as a state machine

Every TCP connection is a state machine. When you `open` a socket, you
transition from CLOSED to SYN-SENT. When the remote side answers, you
go to ESTABLISHED. When you close, you walk through FIN-WAIT and
TIME-WAIT and back to CLOSED. Every one of the packets exchanged is a
transition. Every timeout is a state-machine timer.

Appendix C of this book has more on the TCP state machine. It is a
lovely example of how a small state machine coordinates two machines
across an unreliable network.

## The cloud

By the 2010s, the pattern of running your own servers was starting to
lose to a new model: rent computing time from Amazon, Google, or
Microsoft, and pay per second. This is called **cloud computing.**
The customer doesn't own hardware. The provider does. The customer
pays for CPU-hours, memory-GB-hours, and network egress.

Cloud computing is possible because:

- Fast networks (chapter 15).
- Virtualization (a VM is a whole simulated computer, running on the
  provider's real hardware).
- Containers (isolated processes with their own filesystem view).
- Distributed storage (many disks arranged as one big virtual disk).
- Automation (APIs to spin up and destroy machines in seconds).

Every LLM you use today runs on the cloud. Anthropic, Google, OpenAI,
and DeepSeek all run their models on huge clusters of GPUs in
datacenters they either own or rent. Chapter 16 gets to that.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

- The operating system multiplexes one CPU into many processes,
  gives each its own address space, and mediates access to hardware.
- Unix is the pattern almost every serious OS follows.
- Networking is packet switching plus TCP/IP plus HTTP.
- Everything on the internet is bytes flowing through a state
  machine, hopping across routers.
- The cloud is other people's computers, rented by the second.

The tower is now: hardware → OS → language runtime → your program.
The internet turns that tower into a **forest** of towers cooperating
across cables.

## The loop appears

The OS scheduler is a loop. The network stack is a loop. Every server
is a loop (accept connection, handle request, respond, loop). Every
browser is a loop (fetch URL, render, click, loop). The internet as a
whole is a giant self-perpetuating loop of requests and responses that
has been running for over fifty years and shows no sign of stopping.

## Next

Chapter 16: the final chapter. Cloud, LLMs, and the loop that closes.
Twenty thousand years from the bone to the language model. Meet
Claude, Gemini, OpenAI, and DeepSeek.
")
